{
  "texts": [
    "Instead, the longer response times may result from filtering costs.",
    "To provide convincing evidence for attentional capture, it is therefore necessary to track the spatial locus of attention and show that attention was allocated to the distractor.",
    "Currently, there are two broad types of measures allowing for the localization of attention.",
    "First, measures showing that attention was focused on the distractor location, such as response-compatibility effects, the proportion of overt shifts of attention (i.e., eye movements) made to the distractor relative to non-targets and distractor-elicited ERP components associated with attentional selection (e.g., N2pc; Eimer & Kiss, 2007; Hickey et al., 2006; see also Timing).",
    "Responsecompatibility effects are measured in discrimination tasks where identifying the reported feature requires focused attention."
  ]
}